    {
      title: "Pillar 1: Technical Breakdown",
      subtitle: "What We're Actually Measuring",
      type: "content",
      content: (
        <div className="space-y-6">
          <div className="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg">
            <h3 className="font-bold text-xl mb-3">Components of This Criterion</h3>
            <p className="text-gray-700 mb-4">
              This pillar consolidates three distinct but related aerodynamic parameters:
            </p>
            
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                <div className="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">Front Downforce Consistency</div>
                <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  The front wing must remain attached and generate stable downforce across all speeds. Flow separation at low speeds or excessive loading at high speeds both cause inconsistency.
                </p>
                <div className="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  Measured via: CFD pressure maps, flow visualization, wind tunnel force curves
                </div>
              </div>

              <div className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                <div className="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">Aerodynamic Balance Range</div>
                <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  The percentage of total downforce acting on the front axle should remain within a narrow window. If balance shifts significantly with speed, the car becomes unpredictable.
                </p>
                <div className="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  Measured via: Front/rear wing adjustment sensitivity, CFD balance maps
                </div>
              </div>

              <div className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-blue-500">
                <div className="font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">Minimum Speed Downforce Floor</div>
                <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2">
                  Modern ground effect floors can lose effectiveness dramatically at low speeds. Maintaining at least 40% of maximum downforce at 80 kph ensures the car remains stable in slow corners.
                </p>
                <div className="text-xs text-gray-500">
                  Measured via: CFD velocity fields under floor, pressure distribution analysis
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-blue-600 text-white p-4 rounded-lg">
            <div className="font-bold mb-2">Why Consolidate?</div>
            <p className="text-sm">
              These three parameters all affect the same outcome: whether the car feels consistent to the driver across different speeds. By grouping them, we create a single, actionable design target rather than optimizing three separate (and potentially conflicting) goals.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      )
    },
    {
      title: "Pillar 2: Ride Height Robustness",
      subtitle: "Surviving COTA's Brutal Surface",
      type: "content",
      content: (
        <div className="space-y-6">
          <div className="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-red-600">
            <h3 className="font-bold text-xl mb-3 text-red-900">What Is Ride Height Robustness?</h3>
            <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Ride height robustness measures how tolerant your aerodynamic package is to changes in the car's height above the ground. Ground effect cars generate massive downforce by accelerating air underneath the floor, but this is extremely sensitive to ride height changes.
            </p>
            <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              When a car hits bumps, uses fuel (getting lighter), or experiences suspension compression, the ride height changes. A robust aero package maintains performance despite these variations. A fragile package loses downforce catastrophically or becomes unpredictable.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border-2 border-gray-200">
            <h4 className="font-bold text-lg mb-4">The Physics Problem</h4>
            <div className="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
              <div className="flex items-start">
                <span className="font-bold mr-3 text-red-600">•</span>
                <span><span className="font-bold">Too Low:</span> Floor contacts track surface (plank wear), or edge wing stalls causing sudden downforce loss and potential porpoising</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex items-start">
                <span className="font-bold mr-3 text-red-600">•</span>
                <span><span className="font-bold">Too High:</span> Gap under floor increases, reducing ground effect dramatically. Can lose 2-3% of total downforce per millimeter</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex items-start">
                <span className="font-bold mr-3 text-red-600">•</span>
                <span><span className="font-bold">Variable:</span> Inconsistent ride height through corners means downforce constantly changing, making car unpredictable</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-red-900 text-white p-6 rounded-lg">
            <h4 className="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Target Specification</h4>
            <div className="space-y-2">
              <div className="flex justify-between">
                <span>Downforce loss per 1mm ride height increase:</span>
                <span className="font-bold">&lt;0.8%</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex justify-between">
                <span>Operational heave range:</span>
                <span className="font-bold">8-12mm</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex justify-between">
                <span>Floor stall margin:</span>
                <span className="font-bold">Zero events</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      )
