    {
      title: "Pillar 2: Technical Breakdown",
      subtitle: "Component Parameters",
      type: "content",
      content: (
        <div className="space-y-6">
          <div className="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg">
            <h3 className="font-bold text-xl mb-3">Three Integrated Elements</h3>
            
            <div className="space-y-4">
              <div className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-red-500">
                <div className="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Ride Height Sensitivity</div>
                <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  Quantifies how much downforce is lost as the car rises from its optimal height. Modern floors can be extremely sensitive, losing 1-2% downforce per millimeter. Our target of &lt;0.8% requires sophisticated floor geometry and edge wing design.
                </p>
                <div className="bg-red-50 p-3 rounded text-xs">
                  <div className="font-bold mb-1">Design Solutions:</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Diffuser throat geometry optimized for ride height range</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Edge wing profiles with gradual stall characteristics</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Floor strakes positioned to maintain vortex strength</div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-red-500">
                <div className="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Diffuser Performance Robustness</div>
                <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  The diffuser is the primary downforce generator in ground effect cars. It must contribute at least 35% of rear downforce while tolerating pitch changes (nose up/down) of ±0.5 degrees without flow separation.
                </p>
                <div className="bg-red-50 p-3 rounded text-xs">
                  <div className="font-bold mb-1">Design Solutions:</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Progressive diffuser ramp angles preventing sudden stall</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Kicker elements stabilizing flow reattachment</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Beam wing interaction optimized across pitch range</div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div className="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-red-500">
                <div className="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Front Wing Loading</div>
                <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-3">
                  Front wing must generate sufficient downforce coefficient (Cl,f ≥1.4) for Turn 1 braking stability while remaining effective when ride height changes through bumps. Must not create understeer in slow corners where mechanical grip dominates.
                </p>
                <div className="bg-red-50 p-3 rounded text-xs">
                  <div className="font-bold mb-1">Design Solutions:</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Multi-element configuration with progressive stall margin</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Endplate vortex management reducing wake sensitivity</div>
                  <div className="text-gray-700">• Flap angle optimization across operational envelope</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-red-600 text-white p-4 rounded-lg">
            <div className="font-bold mb-2">Success Metric</div>
            <p className="text-sm">
              Consistent sector times across fuel loads. If times degrade as fuel burns off (ride height increases), the aero package lacks robustness. Target: &lt;0.05s lap time variation across 50kg fuel range.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      )
    },
    {
      title: "Pillar 3: Drag Efficiency",
      subtitle: "Optimizing the Speed-Downforce Tradeoff",
      type: "content",
      content: (
        <div className="space-y-6">
          <div className="bg-gray-700 text-white p-6 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-gray-900">
            <h3 className="font-bold text-xl mb-3">What Is Drag Efficiency?</h3>
            <p className="leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Drag efficiency is the fundamental aerodynamic tradeoff: how much straight-line speed are you sacrificing to generate cornering downforce? It's measured as the lift-to-drag ratio (L/D) - how many units of downforce you get per unit of drag.
            </p>
            <p className="leading-relaxed">
              A high L/D ratio means you can have both good cornering speed AND competitive straight-line speed. A low L/D ratio forces you to choose: either be fast in corners but slow on straights, or vice versa.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div className="bg-green-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
              <div className="font-bold text-green-900 mb-2">Efficient Configuration</div>
              <p className="text-sm text-gray-700">Clean airflow, minimal separation, optimized wing profiles. Generates maximum downforce for minimum drag penalty.</p>
              <div className="text-2xl font-bold text-green-600 mt-3">L/D ≥ 3.2</div>
            </div>
            <div className="bg-red-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
              <div className="font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Inefficient Configuration</div>
              <p className="text-sm text-gray-700">Separated flow, excessive cooling drag, poorly managed tire wakes. Every unit of downforce costs excessive speed.</p>
              <div className="text-2xl font-bold text-red-600 mt-3">L/D &lt; 2.8</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border-2 border-gray-300">
            <h4 className="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Why This Matters Strategically</h4>
            <p className="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-3">
              Drag efficiency determines your race strategy options. High efficiency means:
            </p>
            <div className="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
              <div className="flex items-start">
                <span className="mr-3 text-green-600">✓</span>
                <span>Can defend position on straights while still being fast through corners</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex items-start">
                <span className="mr-3 text-green-600">✓</span>
                <span>Can overtake into Turn 12 hairpin without giving position back on back straight</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex items-start">
                <span className="mr-3 text-green-600">✓</span>
                <span>Flexible strategy - can run higher downforce without severe time loss</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-gray-900 text-white p-6 rounded-lg">
            <h4 className="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Target Specification</h4>
            <div className="space-y-2">
              <div className="flex justify-between">
                <span>Lift-to-drag ratio at race config:</span>
                <span className="font-bold text-green-400">≥3.2</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex justify-between">
                <span>Back straight trap speed:</span>
                <span className="font-bold text-green-400">320+ kph</span>
              </div>
              <div className="flex justify-between">
                <span>Rear stability in crosswinds:</span>
                <span className="font-bold text-green-400">±8° yaw</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      )
    },
    {
      title: "Pillar 3: The COTA Equation",
      subtitle: "Back Straight vs Sector 1",
      type: "content",
      content: (
        <div className="space-y-6">
          <div className="bg-yellow-50 p-6 rounded-lg">
            <h3 className="font-bold text-xl mb-3 text-yellow-900">The Strategic Dilemma</h3>
            <p className="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              COTA's 1.2km back straight is one of the longest in F1, with cars reaching 320-330 kph. But Sector 1 contains some of the most demanding high-speed corners on the calendar. Every kilogram of downforce helps in Sector 1 but costs speed on the straight.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div className="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border-2 border-gray-300">
            <h4 className="font-bold text-lg mb-4">The Numbers</h4>
            <div className="space-y-4">
